{"class":"Article","id":"article","children":[{"class":"Document","id":"e9ea9e57b-fbaf-47fe-b70d-c7617065bc63","children":[{"class":"PageNumbering","id":"eddd4bb9e-0cb5-446b-8bf9-cee5e272d71c","children":[],"numbering":"gobble"},{"class":"MakeTitle","id":"ee78d98c4-1cd3-4f91-b815-23c3ff8189fd","children":[]},{"class":"NewPage","id":"edc6b3954-6b94-4dd9-9e63-8cf3caa15ed5","children":[]},{"class":"PageNumbering","id":"ec6f06c4c-eb6e-4ecd-9c2f-4b7f6fbbc5bb","children":[],"numbering":"arabic"},{"class":"Section","id":"e7b02c4f9-f3bc-4477-b54c-f6d7cd4aaf45","children":[{"class":"Paragraph","id":"e6a9bd601-1751-484f-8164-8d4f416f3a7a","children":[{"class":"Text","id":"e2c2e6ace-bc8e-4e4d-b5b4-8417a5b01d83","children":[],"text":"A pendulum is a mass connected at the end of an arm of constant length which is allowed to pivot about a fixed point. We shall find that they produce oscillatory or almost oscillatory behaviour depending on whether or not air resistance is taken into account."}]},{"class":"Paragraph","id":"e7bf6a422-2210-4f02-90be-0978c22edfe1","children":[{"class":"Text","id":"e20772d60-02af-4dc2-839b-f2ede242ada7","children":[],"text":"We shall first define a cartesian coordinate system with the aforementioned fixed point at the origin. We will define "},{"class":"InlineMaths","id":"ea62cebaf-4800-426f-acc6-30d666e2a13b","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"ea092bcfc-a4cc-4a96-81ea-c5b4fadd3d65","children":[],"var":"r"}]},{"class":"Text","id":"e8a2ad60c-4465-4aef-886e-776dd37a99f6","children":[],"text":" to be the length of the pendulum's arm and "},{"class":"InlineMaths","id":"e080cde82-f9aa-4a32-8d53-a6469b10dd04","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e073ec480-c9f3-49ea-a0dd-731973f16937","children":[],"var":"θ"},{"class":"Brackets","id":"e170a10d8-908a-4b7b-842a-fbba9215f339","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e7cf8f4a9-6683-4842-a85b-064830dda14d","children":[],"var":"t"}],"square":false}]},{"class":"Text","id":"ea89e9407-22f0-4db1-932d-23ac560c1634","children":[],"text":" to be the angle counterclockwise from the y-axis of our coordinate plane to the arm of the pendulum at any time "},{"class":"InlineMaths","id":"e13dfbcda-ba09-44ac-8be9-59852f7f368b","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e51a2a96a-1b51-4085-b452-b328e6a62e81","children":[],"var":"t"}]},{"class":"Text","id":"e70dbb1ae-e0b5-4d95-a06f-b606b97c2edb","children":[],"text":"."}]},{"class":"Paragraph","id":"edddf4419-ec45-4a0b-9d04-aee7608395f2","children":[{"class":"Text","id":"e2232857f-65ae-4031-a338-9137ed795ded","children":[],"text":"We can now define the position of the mass at any time "},{"class":"InlineMaths","id":"e3cf7d515-d002-4817-92a5-b89045a74694","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e5bee40e8-1a5f-4616-ab1c-8957ab979044","children":[],"var":"t"}]},{"class":"Text","id":"e7465bf4c-55f6-49ee-b3db-cb878fa6a05c","children":[],"text":" by using the constant distance from the origin and the angle function "},{"class":"InlineMaths","id":"e2965a2c3-48e3-4424-bd28-9a94217a8ed3","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e974b452d-33ee-4e0f-9ff7-523b09a9921d","children":[],"var":"θ"},{"class":"Brackets","id":"e36fec239-df8a-4c98-abc7-aa9ae96b9970","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e080d9257-0b9a-4fff-a2db-d434173397c7","children":[],"var":"t"}],"square":false}]},{"class":"Text","id":"ec614643d-8f35-4d22-819d-4968d9583b3e","children":[],"text":" to construct a right angle triangle. Using the sine and cosine functions we find that the position of the mass at time "},{"class":"InlineMaths","id":"e1b1936c9-1a26-4f65-8d5c-713cd3e33c0b","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"ea7a1a705-52b7-4b26-9735-644dc31740aa","children":[],"var":"t"}]},{"class":"Text","id":"e23551f1f-e271-4a4b-a414-4cba97a160ed","children":[],"text":" is "},{"class":"InlineMaths","id":"efbee3619-76f2-4f1b-988c-653af4d7dbdb","children":[{"class":"Brackets","id":"e54f6b938-cbee-4ddb-9542-39304a47cd64","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"ea43dc7f1-43b8-4430-ad31-f33ed2d33caf","children":[],"var":"r"},{"class":"Function","id":"ea52f040d-df56-400c-9ad9-e1f326ee6e99","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e6fcac23d-6a95-4f8f-8099-d42917a6f759","children":[],"var":"θ"},{"class":"Brackets","id":"e340d6a02-9ab1-4d14-8a2b-dde5ce329f76","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e2d0a179e-3889-48ff-9e04-472c395b82cd","children":[],"var":"t"}],"square":false}],"func":"sin"},{"class":"Comma","id":"ee709eb40-fdaf-4dce-9594-0ae90367f453","children":[]},{"class":"UnaryMinus","id":"effa0d12d-9315-44da-8542-446b0e6f45e0","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e3b22f32c-8def-48af-ac07-8ed431010af0","children":[],"var":"r"},{"class":"Function","id":"e4a99a12a-6f9a-4c4b-be88-685ae091d99d","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"eba122b84-537f-466b-87af-ed8cff62d26f","children":[],"var":"θ"},{"class":"Brackets","id":"e2a3eb329-a65c-4cbf-be6c-9b1beba4629a","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e8ba75f16-5729-42b3-8764-fb66da7ca42b","children":[],"var":"t"}],"square":false}],"func":"cos"}]}],"square":false}]},{"class":"Text","id":"ece8010ae-5bfc-4b13-9ed9-2ed7b6df946c","children":[],"text":"."}]},{"class":"Paragraph","id":"e12a0f945-2c71-44dc-a10c-570a378c1e92","children":[{"class":"Text","id":"edf5c339b-b9e2-4e4e-9e4c-5de40b427ce2","children":[],"text":"We now analyse the forces at work on the mass of the pendulum at any time "},{"class":"InlineMaths","id":"eead6121f-c5a2-418e-8155-34eb047b15ce","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e192eb0a1-46b0-48c1-85a2-f6532bbd0d1d","children":[],"var":"t"}]},{"class":"Text","id":"e1bbfe910-d403-440b-a790-a657b6a6eaa9","children":[],"text":". This is where our work diverges into two separate cases depending on whether or not we deem the contributions of air resistance to be negligible. We shall start with the far simpler case assuming that it does not have a noticeable impact before investigating what difficulties arise from including contributions of air resistance."}]},{"class":"SubSection","id":"e6b3c4f4a-ccda-4585-9f6d-a7c2c991e88b","children":[{"class":"Paragraph","id":"edcd97f98-7735-41c4-b978-65be41950c6f","children":[{"class":"Text","id":"e5b88cdc9-be9c-4106-9e50-d758ea681544","children":[],"text":"If we assume the contributions of air resistance to the resultant force on the mass to be negligible, we have only two forces acting on our mass: gravity and the centripetal force. Gravity acts downwards with a magnitude proportional to the mass "},{"class":"InlineMaths","id":"edd5f9a7b-54c5-41ff-bba5-311c1121623a","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e477ad4ee-209a-482f-8447-409280e34b4d","children":[],"var":"m"}]},{"class":"Text","id":"e51666fc3-fa87-49b6-87a1-0f932843a73e","children":[],"text":" where the constant of proportionality is "},{"class":"InlineMaths","id":"e04f44b83-7571-410f-b92e-5aae5b7485ca","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"efeb5f37d-26bd-4551-a162-454dca595163","children":[],"var":"g"},{"class":"Approx","id":"e03890fd8-511d-4b78-8494-f0891f0cb849","children":[]},{"class":"Number","id":"e709188d2-0916-4dab-8d90-ec971ae62fc7","children":[],"num":9.81},{"class":"Text","id":"e8aa61e3a-30bf-4ed0-9ab1-fc114e7b6555","children":[],"text":"ms"},{"class":"Power","id":"e73cdea96-bf5e-42d8-986c-22d9e5891046","children":[{"class":"UnaryMinus","id":"e72c8e922-af84-414f-837b-b14892578e5e","children":[{"class":"Number","id":"e2760ad89-f557-4fd8-8ea8-c39ddeea92ba","children":[],"num":2}]}]}]},{"class":"Text","id":"ed7ff14df-78a0-4be2-adfe-a7e4a661e9f7","children":[],"text":". The centripetal force is the force keeping the mass attached to the pendulum's arm and it arises due to Newton's third law of motion (every action has an equal and opposite reaction). Therefore, we know it will be equal in magnitude but opposite in direction to the component of the force of gravity "},{"class":"InlineMaths","id":"e64848a7b-1ae3-4b21-aadd-e91259de495b","children":[{"class":"Vector","id":"ef5840a3e-6007-4961-af97-cc75bb471f80","children":[],"var":"g"}]},{"class":"Text","id":"eb345d81b-76ad-4c6f-a047-cb7a4f76735b","children":[],"text":" in the direction from the fixed pivot point to the mass. As we placed the origin at the fixed point, the vector from the fixed point to the mass is the position vector of the mass, "},{"class":"InlineMaths","id":"e4a31c5d0-bd4e-4b2a-95df-d4b7bc7753f5","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e2c093ca3-1efe-47c1-988b-a7da8bb6d888","children":[],"var":"r"},{"class":"Brackets","id":"e8a89ff2e-3f55-457f-9b25-c4a253e944c7","children":[{"class":"Function","id":"e69ddc211-5436-4db6-b5aa-69644bf1bc43","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e6c927494-7df0-4127-8e33-92cd4008bb1c","children":[],"var":"θ"},{"class":"Brackets","id":"ec8064216-01f7-4778-8573-a398f10a2b70","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"efed43ffc-2595-46c8-9187-db37887bdb79","children":[],"var":"t"}],"square":false}],"func":"sin"},{"class":"Comma","id":"e0690a389-8e9e-4f2b-a130-c9c02339cab0","children":[]},{"class":"UnaryMinus","id":"eb8213c30-1b5e-45e2-999b-f70b80b50142","children":[{"class":"Function","id":"e94e28558-fa0a-4026-81ed-418066afd242","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e4de54e3c-e270-442a-a654-1b2a3d6ded39","children":[],"var":"θ"},{"class":"Brackets","id":"eb9c546f7-631e-4f17-9391-456f06cac868","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e256afa78-c090-4650-bffe-ec0590c13b7a","children":[],"var":"t"}],"square":false}],"func":"cos"}]}],"square":false}]},{"class":"Text","id":"e19488129-ee39-41af-a3f1-2cd27d0f98b7","children":[],"text":". The distance from the fixed point to the mass is defined to be "},{"class":"InlineMaths","id":"e9743adac-e637-4c57-8479-63bbf019b683","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e71a89244-9968-4fc7-8c1a-6981d57e7f9e","children":[],"var":"r"}]},{"class":"Text","id":"efef2d479-4ada-411e-a204-7d31ea12913c","children":[],"text":" and hence by dividing by this we find the unit vector "},{"class":"InlineMaths","id":"e93bc0145-ca03-4f60-be3c-711252e23273","children":[{"class":"Vector","id":"e2b2c000b-efa0-4860-9a44-dfa791fcabd6","children":[],"var":"d"},{"class":"Equals","id":"e85150586-9655-4489-82e7-6620a587466e","children":[]},{"class":"Brackets","id":"e70b98b1b-f2fc-464b-b0e6-be18b0335e7a","children":[{"class":"Function","id":"e0f091569-5205-452f-8d5d-e1f8ed35c225","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e246912a0-1ba1-429e-bbf4-bc2ea894360d","children":[],"var":"θ"},{"class":"Brackets","id":"e7a7cdbc1-0d22-4948-9f4a-cd03d5883263","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e9917f80e-a64f-4141-9be2-262990257116","children":[],"var":"t"}],"square":false}],"func":"sin"},{"class":"Comma","id":"e9d9ffa80-c309-4f89-813f-5739d870064a","children":[]},{"class":"UnaryMinus","id":"eb0e6d274-38f6-4ff5-ac85-5bcfe53e0afd","children":[{"class":"Function","id":"ece484d5d-b732-4944-a209-f09776617468","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"e40bb9eb5-74a4-4b1e-89ae-1a423eea27b5","children":[],"var":"θ"},{"class":"Brackets","id":"e4150b624-7460-4815-afdf-de7d75e1ae9c","children":[{"class":"Variable","id":"ef0f2e07a-5b96-4fdd-a560-b76093524fb8","children":[],"var":"t"}],"square":false}],"func":"cos"}]}],"square":true}]},{"class":"Text","id":"e985cd982-84cf-4cca-a2c9-95a11e5076a6","children":[],"text":". We therefore may find the centripetal force "},{"class":"InlineMaths","id":"e77c25ad8-044d-437f-aac8-e935e793f354","children":[{"class":"Vector","id":"e057574ff-3d23-4484-96bf-95066aefdd53","children":[],"var":"c"}]},{"class":"Text","id":"e16b658e8-5558-4418-8563-3c9bd624462c","children":[],"text":" via an application of the dot product as follows"}]}],"title":"Assuming air resistance is negligible"}],"title":"Pendulums"}]}],"root":"#root","packages":[{"name":"amsmath"},{"name":"amsthm"},{"name":"amssymb"},{"name":"booktabs"},{"name":"graphicx"},{"name":"array"},{"name":"geometry","options":{"margin":"1.5in"}}],"author":"Benjamin Jones","title":"Simple Oscillators"}